            <article class="grid-2-3">
                <h2>Trying and making VR for the first time —</h2>
                <div>
                    <p>
                        The main problem was that no one in the team had any previous experience with VR, nor even as users. So our first step was to borrow an <b>HTC Vive</b> and a beefy laptop from the <b>Ericsson Lab</b> and get our feet wet as we sailed previously unknown waters.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        We learned a couple of things doing it, but two were critical insights. First, we did not have the necessary skills to develop the experience ourselves (even though we had some game engine experience) on such a short deadline. Secondly, as the first introduction to VR for many of the people at the summit, we needed to keep it simple enough and as motion sickness safe as possible.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        To tackle these issues, we created a preliminary concept of what the experience would be like, and after convincing the stakeholders to allocate budget, we enlisted the much more experienced folks at <a href="https://www.mediamonks.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Media Monks Stockholm</a>.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </article>

            <article class="grid-2-3">
                <h2>From 2D to 3D —</h2>
                <div>
                    <p>
                        Rewinding just a bit to the concept phase, we also had the challenge of making something that made reasonable sense, as part of a future Ericsson product portfolio. After some ideation, we decided to adapt the geolocation feature on the <b>Ericsson Security Manager</b> into virtual reality.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        To visualize the concept, I created a 3D model of the globe in <b>Cinema 4D</b>, rendered out an image that showed the overall art direction and environment. After that, it was just a matter of mocking up the different HUD (heads up display) UI elements and create a rough experience flow in <b>Illustrator</b>.
                    </p>
                </div>
